// Contributor: Adrian, Kevin
// Reviewer: Lucas
// Reference: https://medium.com/@truvis.thornton/visual-studio-code-embedded-reverse-shell-and-how-to-block-create-sentinel-detection-and-add-e864ebafaf6d
// Description: Threat actors may use embedded reverse shell (remote tunnelling) to obtain command and control on a device using Microsoft signed binaries. This analytic looks for traffic to the domains associated with tunneling. 
// Handling Guidance: Look for InitiatingProcessFolderPath to see what initiated the event (downloads folder is likely a big red flag). Look at the device events
// Change notes
// ------------
// 04/05/24 Adrian,Kevin - Initial version
// 04/08/24 Lucas - Updated description, alert grouping, and lookback for production
// 04/09/24 Adrian - added exclusions for Dev users to filter out FPs
// 04/11/24 Adrian - casted AccountName to lower to fix issue in IdentityInfo table
// 07/18/2024 Adrian - updated zscaler exclusion
// 07/26/2024 Wajahat, Kevin, James - Switched department and job title exclusions
// 08/01/2024 Wajahat and Kevin - added zscaler exclusion 
//08/22/2024 Grover Mewborn - updated zscaler exclusion
//09/13/2024 Wajahat Malik and Sufian Tanveer - Changed the whole alert logic to include all the department
DeviceEvents
| where InitiatingProcessCommandLine has "enable-remote"
| where InitiatingProcessCommandLine has "pipe"
| summarize arg_max(TimeGenerated, *) by DeviceName
| project
    TimeGenerated,
    AccountName,
    DeviceName,
    InitiatingProcessCommandLine,
    InitiatingProcessFileName,
    ActionType,
    InitiatingProcessFolderPath,
    InitiatingProcessParentFileName,
    InitiatingProcessVersionInfoProductName
